What you'll learn today

By the end of this lesson, you will be able to:

  • Explain the difference between a database table and a spreadsheet table.
  • Describe primary keys and why they’re useful.
  • Choose the right tool for a given data task.

How you'll know you've got it

  • Design a small table with a sensible primary key.
  • Write or read a simple query / use a spreadsheet filter.
  • Give one real example where each tool fits best.

Key Vocabulary

Table — a set of rows (records) and columns (fields) in a database.
Record — one row of related data (e.g., one student).
Field — a column that stores one type of data (e.g., Date of Birth).
Primary Key — a field that uniquely identifies each record.
Foreign Key — a field that links to a primary key in another table.
Query — a question to the database to get certain data.
Filter — a spreadsheet tool to show only rows that match a rule.
Validation — checks to keep data sensible and clean.

Main Activities

CS Track – Mini Database

  1. Design a Students table: StudentID (PK), FirstName, TutorGroup, DoB.
  2. Write a simple query to list students in a chosen tutor group.
  3. Extension: add a Clubs table and think about a link.
-- Example SQL
SELECT StudentID, FirstName, TutorGroup
FROM Students
WHERE TutorGroup = '10A';

IT Track – Spreadsheet Data Handling

  1. Enter a 10‑row dataset (e.g., club name, members, fees).
  2. Sort by members; filter to show fees > 5.
  3. Create a bar chart and add a clear title.

Compare & Reflect

  • When would a spreadsheet be enough? When is a database better?
  • How do keys stop mistakes like duplicates?
  • Where might you use both together?

Plenary – Hands‑Up Task

  • 🟥 Hands up if you preferred Databases (CS).
  • 🟦 Hands up if you preferred Spreadsheets (IT).
  • 🟨 Hands up if you liked both.
  • 🟩 Hands up if you’re still unsure.
